08404nam a22011415i 9783110630367DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97831106303677 a10.1515/97831106303672doi  a(DE-B1597)502426  a(OCoLC)1135590429  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh00aMetaphor in Foreign Language Instruction /ced. by Ana María Piquer-Píriz, Rafael Alejo-González. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 289 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aApplications of Cognitive Linguistics [ACL] ,x1861-4078 ;v4200tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tMetaphor in L2 Instruction: Key Issues -- tPart I. Theoretical Considerations: Reviews and Perspectives -- tThe Particularities of Metaphorical Experience: An Appreciation of Fiona MacArthur’s Metaphor Scholarship -- tTaking Stock after Three Decades: “On Teaching Metaphor” Revisited -- tFigurative Language and Young L2 Learners -- tMetaphor and Spanish as a Foreign Language -- tPart II. New Empirical Studies -- tPart II. 1. Learners’ Use and Knowledge of L2 Figurative language -- tIs Comfort Purple or Green? Word-colour Associations in the First and Second Language -- tMetaphorical Reasoning in Comprehension and Translation: An Analysis of Metaphor in Multiple Translations -- tMetaphorical Alignment in Cross-Cultural Office Hours’ Consultations -- tDevelopment of L2 Metaphorical Production -- tMeasuring Secondary-School L2 Learners Vocabulary Knowledge: Metaphorical Competence as Part of General Lexical Competence -- tPart II. 2. Fostering Knowledge of L2 Figurative Language -- tUsing Literal Underpinnings to Help Learners Remember Figurative Idioms: Does the Connection Need to Be Crystal Clear? -- t“The Manage of Two Kingdoms Must”: An Analysis of Metaphor in Two CLIL Textbooks -- tAn Enactment-Based Approach to the Teaching of Metaphoric Expressions: A Case of Saudi EFL Learners -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aExploring the role that metaphor plays in our linguistic and conceptual systems from a Cognitive Linguistics (CL)-oriented perspective has attracted a great deal of attention for the past three decades. The analysis of the applications of some theoretical tenets of CL (mainly the notion of linguistic motivation) has been particularly fruitful in foreign language (L2) instruction. However, despite some important research findings related to the presentation of word meanings as systematically connected, metaphor is still rarely included as an important part of language courses designed for L2 learners. This volume explores the important role of metaphor in L2 instruction by presenting both theoretical accounts and empirical studies into the topic. Part I comprises four theoretical chapters that touch upon issues of continuing relevance to the discipline (e.g. why metaphor is relevant for L2 learners and how it can be effectively taught) and introduce areas in need of further research (metaphor in L2 instruction in languages other than English or metaphor and young L2 learners). Part II consists of eight empirical studies that illustrate methodological challenges and best practices when analyzing metaphor in real L2 contexts.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aMetapher. 4aSpracherwerb. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCross-cultural Communication.  aL2.  aMetaphor.  aTeaching.1 aAlejo-González, Rafael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlejo-González, Rafael, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vo